What I was forgetting was the differing types of operators (character) and operands (double). Once I realized this, within the visit() method, we can check if the node is an operator (internal node), further check which operator (+, -, /, *), then call accept() method on both left and right nodes (casting both to doubles) with the actual operator in-between.

Example:

    if (n.getContent() == (Object) &#39;+&#39;)
            d = (Double) n.getLeft().accept(this) + (Double) n.getRight().accept(this);


d being a Double variable. This will continue being called until we reach an operand (leaf node), which we check for within the visit() method by:

    // If node has no children, we are at an operand (Double)
	if (n.getLeft() == null &amp;&amp; n.getRight() == null)
			return Double.parseDouble(n.getContent().toString());

This will return the value to original accept() call and will add the two values together in this instance.

